channel.title: Interleaved RSS Feed
channel.description: This is an interleaved feed of the most recent entries from each RSS source, skipping any feeds with errors.

item.title: Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary Visits Ukraine
item.description: Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary, who has resisted European military and financial aid for Ukraine, met with President Volodymyr Zelensky in Kyiv.

item.title: Middle East Crisis: Large Crowds Flee Southern Gaza Areas Under Israeli Evacuation Order
item.description: Israel’s military says its forces fired at areas of Khan Younis from which a rocket barrage was launched. Even as Israel prepares to focus on ‘targeted raids,’ it is telling people to leave a large swath of Gaza.

item.title: New law in Iowa allows 14-year-olds get a driver’s license
item.description: Minors allowed to ferry themselves to work and school.

item.title: Israeli Generals, Low on Munitions, Want a Truce in Gaza
item.description: Israel’s military leadership wants a cease-fire with Hamas in case a bigger war breaks out in Lebanon, security officials say. It has also concluded that a truce would be the swiftest way to free hostages.

item.title: Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary Visits Ukraine
item.description: Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary, who has resisted European military and financial aid for Ukraine, met with President Volodymyr Zelensky in Kyiv.

item.title: Planning decision for London’s controversial ‘Undershaft’ skyscraper delayed as objections mount over the city’s tallest tower
item.description: The chairman of Lloyd's of London complained the skyscraper would rob London of an important public square.

item.title: A Fractured Supreme Court’s Decisions Remade America in 2024
item.description: Amid signs of dysfunction and disarray, Chief Justice John Roberts reasserted his authority, while the influence of Justices Clarence Thomas and Samuel Alito waned.

item.title: Israeli Generals, Low on Munitions, Want a Truce in Gaza
item.description: Israel’s military leadership wants a cease-fire with Hamas in case a bigger war breaks out in Lebanon, security officials say. It has also concluded that a truce would be the swiftest way to free hostages.

item.title: Wingstop’s U.K. sober millennial chief walks to work from his Hampstead Heath apartment and has $25 lunches from London’s hottest luxury gym
item.description: Tom Grogan tells Fortune how he lives his “Good Life” from what he spends his bonus money on to his go-to $25 lunch order.

item.title: Supreme Court Won’t Hear Gun Cases on High-Powered Rifles and Disarming Felons
item.description: The court, which issued two major decisions on guns in the term that ended Monday, does not seem ready to return to the subject.

item.title: U.K. Nurse Lucy Letby Convicted of Attempted Murder in Retrial
item.description: Ms. Letby, who was previously found guilty in a string of murders and attempted murders, was retried and found guilty of another attempted murder.

item.title: 8 best secured credit cards to help build or repair your credit
item.description: We compared dozens of secured credit cards across numerous financial institutions and weighed minimum account deposits, annual fees, credit limits, rewards, and more.

item.title: June Leaf, Artist Who Explored the Female Form, Dies at 94
item.description: Womanly power was a recurring theme of her work, expressed in idiosyncratic sculpture and paintings that did not align with prevailing trends.

item.title: Hurricane Beryl Advances to Category 5 in the Caribbean, Approaching Jamaica
item.description: Officials said the storm caused extreme damage to islands in Grenada and St. Vincent and the Grenadines. No storm has become a Category 5 this early in the season.

item.title: Ken Griffin is hitting pause on the AI hype, saying he’s unconvinced the tech will start replacing jobs in the next 3 years
item.description: “For a number of reasons, I am not convinced that these models will achieve that type of breakthrough in the near future.”
